<p>J. W. Alexander, 1849, in the Schaff-Gilman <em>Lib. of Religious Poetry</em>.</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>O Sacred Head, now wounded,<br />
  With grief and shame bow‚Äôd down,<br />
  Now scornfully surrounded,<br />
  With thorns, Thy only crown.<br />
  O Sacred Head, what glory<br />
  What bliss till now was Thine<br />
  Yet, though despised and gory,<br />
  I joy to call Thee mine.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>(Gerhardt IV) What Thou, my Lord, hast suffered,<br />
  Was all for sinner‚Äôs gain:<br />
  Mine, mine was the transgression<br />
  But Thine the deadly pain.<br />
  Lo, here I fall, my Savior:<br />
  ‚ÄòTis I deserve Thy place;<br />
  Look on me with Thy favour,<br />
  Vouchsafe to me Thy grace.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>(Gerhardt VII) The joy can ne‚Äôer be spoken,<br />
  Above all joys beside,<br />
